4HHB | Human HemoglobinBiological Role: Hemoglobin is the vital iron-containing oxygen-transport metalloprotein found in the red blood cells of all vertebrates. Its primary job is to pick up oxygen in the lungs and release it into tissues throughout the body, while returning carbon dioxide back to the lungs.Structural Mechanics: It functions as a heterotetramer, composed of two $\alpha$ (alpha) and two $\beta$ (beta) subunits. Each subunit encloses a non-covalently bound heme group—a ring structure containing a central iron ion ($Fe^{2+}$). The 4HHB entry captures the Tense (T) state (deoxyhemoglobin), which represents the low-affinity structure before oxygen snaps into place and shifts the entire protein conformation into the Relaxed (R) state.
